## LLM Architecture — OpenRouter

All LLM calls go through **OpenRouter** (not directly to Gemini/OpenAI/Anthropic):
- Single API key in 1Password — OpenRouter manages all provider keys
- OpenAI-compatible API (`baseURL: https://openrouter.ai/api/v1`)
- Model IDs use `provider/model` format: `google/gemini-2.5-flash`, `openai/gpt-4o-mini`, etc.
- Handles all parameter normalization, context window enforcement, token counting differences across models
- New models available immediately when they launch — just update the model ID in admin dashboard
- Built-in fallback routing configured per pipeline step
- Returns cost-per-call in response → logged to `api_calls` table automatically

Our thin wrapper (`llm.complete()`):
1. Reads model ID from `pipeline_config` for the given step
2. Calls OpenRouter via OpenAI SDK
3. Logs everything (prompts, response, tokens, cost) to `api_calls` table
4. Returns normalized result to pipeline step

Adding a new model = update one row in Supabase. Zero code changes.

---

## Why Railway (not Vercel) for the Worker

Vercel is serverless — functions are hard-killed after 300 seconds. Our pipeline takes 10-20 minutes (multiple rounds of Exa research + LLM synthesis). Railway runs a persistent Node.js process with no timeout constraints, full log access, and full redeploy control.

---

## Pipeline (Step by Step)

### Step 0 — Email Ingest
- MailerSend receives forwarded email at `add@ai.deckdrop.io`
- POSTs multipart payload to Railway webhook endpoint `/webhook/mailersend`
- Worker parses: sender email, subject, body text, attachments (PDF/PPTX)
- Validates sender exists in `users` table and has ≥1 credit
- Creates `jobs` row with `status: queued`, responds 200 immediately
- Background worker picks up job from Supabase queue

### Step 1 — Company Extraction
Model: `Gemini 2.5 Flash-Lite` (cheap, fast)
- Extract from email body + subject: company name, URL, description
- If pitch deck attached: PDF/PPTX → Markdown text extraction
- Generate **multiple keyword-rich descriptions** in different framings:
  - Functional: "what it does"
  - Customer/problem: "who it serves + what problem"
  - Category/market: "vertical and horizontal positioning"
  - Technical approach (if applicable)
- These become Exa search queries in Step 2

### Step 2 — Competitor Discovery (all parallel)
Uses Exa.ai API with `type: "company"` filter throughout.

**Layer 1 (parallel):**
- `exa.findSimilar(url, { numResults: 20 })` → raw competitors
- `exa.search(description_functional, { type: "company" })`
- `exa.search(description_customer, { type: "company" })`
- `exa.search(description_category, { type: "company" })`
- `exa.search(company_name + " competitors alternative", { type: "company" })`

**Layer 2 (configurable: 1–3 layers):**
- Take top N competitors from Layer 1 (configurable, default 5)
- For each: `exa.findSimilar(competitor_url)` — "competitors of competitors"
- Merge all results, deduplicate by normalized URL

### Step 3 — Competitor Enrichment
- For each unique competitor (up to `max_competitors`, default 15):
  - `exa.getContents(url)` → full page text
  - Structured profile: name, URL, description, customer, differentiators, funding signals

### Step 4 — Research Synthesis
Model: configurable (default `Gemini 2.5 Flash`)
- System prompt + user prompt: both editable in admin dashboard
- Input: index company info + all competitor profiles + raw content
- Output: structured Markdown report:
  - Executive Summary
  - Index Company Analysis
  - Market Overview
  - Competitive Landscape (table)
  - Competitor Deep Dives (top 5–8)
  - Positioning Map (text-based 2×2)
  - Market Sizing
  - Investment Considerations
  - Data Sources

### Step 5 — Gap Analysis (configurable on/off)
Model: `Gemini 2.5 Flash-Lite`
- LLM reviews draft, identifies missing critical info
- Generates targeted Exa follow-up queries
- Runs queries, appends content, re-synthesizes
- Max rounds: configurable (default 1)

### Step 6 — PDF Generation
- Markdown → HTML via `marked.js`
- Professional CSS template applied (print-optimized)
- `@react-pdf/renderer` or Puppeteer renders PDF (pure JS, no browser binary needed)
- Future: CSS Grid 2×2 competitor positioning chart
- PDF stored in Supabase Storage

### Step 7 — Email Delivery
- MailerSend sends PDF attachment to original sender
- CC: inbox@deckdrop.io
- Deduct 1 credit from user
- Update job status to `completed`

---

## Cost Model

| Component | Cost per report (est.) |
|-----------|----------------------|
| Exa searches (Layers 1+2 + enrichment) | ~$0.10–0.30 |
| Gemini 2.5 Flash-Lite (extraction + gap) | ~$0.01–0.05 |
| Gemini 2.5 Flash (synthesis) | ~$0.10–0.40 |
| PDF generation | ~$0.00 (compute) |
| MailerSend (email out) | ~$0.001 |
| **Total** | **~$0.30–0.80** |

vs. Gemini Deep Research with grounding: ~$5–20/report

